\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces {Top: Participant- and item-level estimates for the Arousal model parameters, under the distribution of their point-estimates. Reliable effects are characterised by a higher between-group variability (the dispersion of the distribution of point-estimates) relative to their within-group variability (the average uncertainty of individual estimates, reflected by the error bars). For example, the Intercept shows good reliability here, whereas the participant-level interactions with the AI-Generated label condition show low reliability. Bottom: Correlation matrix between participant-level estimates from the Arousal model and individual-difference measures. The model parameters show low to non-existent correlations with all individual characteristics, indicating that sensitivity to the label is not associated with the individual characteristics measured here.}{}}}{11}{figure.caption.19}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig-corr}{{4}{11}{{Top: Participant- and item-level estimates for the Arousal model parameters, under the distribution of their point-estimates. Reliable effects are characterised by a higher between-group variability (the dispersion of the distribution of point-estimates) relative to their within-group variability (the average uncertainty of individual estimates, reflected by the error bars). For example, the Intercept shows good reliability here, whereas the participant-level interactions with the AI-Generated label condition show low reliability. Bottom: Correlation matrix between participant-level estimates from the Arousal model and individual-difference measures. The model parameters show low to non-existent correlations with all individual characteristics, indicating that sensitivity to the label is not associated with the individual characteristics measured here.}{\label {fig-corr}}}{figure.caption.19}{}}
